# CONSULT-45 — Zone-in load "jerk": Lateral-angle analysis
# Consultant: fresh Sonnet (lateral / out-of-the-box angle)
# Date: 2026-06-20

---

## Framing

This analysis takes the lateral angle: what differences between the MSVC v145/C++20 rebuild
and the original VS2003 retail binary could cause zone-in main-thread hitches, BEYOND the
confirmed runtime VS-compile (Fact A). The crew's other angles cover the compile detail,
disk cache design, and synchronous load mapping. I focus on allocation cost, STL, texture
pool behavior, debug overhead leaking into Release, and a few lateral catches.

All findings are based on direct code inspection of:
- `src/engine/shared/library/sharedMemoryManager/src/shared/MemoryManager.cpp`
- `src/engine/client/application/Direct3d9/src/win32/Direct3d9_TextureData.cpp`
- `src/engine/client/application/Direct3d9/src/win32/Direct3d9_HlslRewrite.cpp`
- `src/engine/client/application/Direct3d9/src/win32/Direct3d9_VertexShaderData.cpp`
- `src/engine/shared/library/sharedFile/src/shared/ZlibFile.cpp`
- `src/engine/shared/library/sharedDebug/src/shared/Report.cpp`
- `src/game/client/application/SwgClient/build/win32/SwgClient.vcxproj`

---

## Candidate 1: MemoryManager global CRITICAL_SECTION — process-wide serialization point

**What it is.** Every `MemoryManager::allocate()` and `::free()` call wraps the entire
tree-search + block split/merge in a single `ms_criticalSection->enter()/leave()` at
MemoryManager.cpp:1216 and 1365/1604. The lock type is a Win32 `CRITICAL_SECTION`
(RecursiveMutex.h:36). This is a process-global, single-threaded-access serializer.

**Zone-in load vs retail.** The retail binary almost certainly used SOE's SmartHeap
(widely used in late-1990s/early-2000s SOE titles) or the CRT malloc, which both use
small-block free-lists without a large binary-search-tree traversal per allocation.
Our MemoryManager uses a Knuth-style best-fit ternary search tree
(addToFreeList / removeFromFreeList / searchFreeList in MemoryManager.cpp:941–1159).
On a warm heap with hundreds of blocks the worst-case tree depth grows with O(log N)
live allocations. The zone-in path creates a large number of new objects (textures,
geometry, shader objects, etc.) on the main thread.

**Magnitude assessment: MED-LOW.** On a single-threaded main loop (which this is),
there is no lock contention — EnterCriticalSection on an uncontested CS is ~5ns
(a few instructions). The tree traversal per alloc is the real cost: in a heap
with say 50k live blocks the searchFreeList walk is O(log 50k) = ~16 comparisons,
each touching a different cache line (the tree is scatter-allocated). At zone-in
you might do tens of thousands of allocations in a short window; if the tree height
is large and the free-block tree is fragmented (which grows worse over a session),
each alloc can be a cache-miss chain. This would manifest as a moderate background
drag rather than a per-frame spike.

**Debug-specific wrinkle.** In Debug builds (`ms_debugProfileAllocate`) there is a
PROFILER_BLOCK_ENTER/LEAVE per alloc (MemoryManager.cpp:1195–1196,1371). Also
`ms_debugVerifyGuardPatterns`/`ms_debugVerifyFreePatterns` trigger a full O(N) heap
walk on every alloc/free (MemoryManager.cpp:1197–1198). If either flag is on by
default in any configuration, Debug is dramatically slower. But flags default to 0
in the source; the real Debug pain point is `_ITERATOR_DEBUG_LEVEL=2` (see candidate 4).

**Retail comparison.** SmartHeap (Micro Quill) uses separate size-class free-lists
and does not do a search per alloc in the common case — it is effectively O(1) for
the most common allocation sizes. Our ternary-tree allocator at full heap occupancy
is categorically slower per-alloc.

**What to measure:**
- Add a PixCounter that increments a global cycle counter around the `ms_criticalSection->enter()` block in allocate(). Read via the in-game profiler or PixCounter dump.
- Alternatively: PIX/Intel VTune sampling profile during cantina zone-in — look for `searchFreeList` or `addToFreeList` appearing in the hot-path.
- A/B: set `#define DISABLE_MEMORY_MANAGER 1` (MemoryManager.cpp:38) in a test build, which falls through to the CRT `malloc`/`free`. If zone-in hitches visibly improve, the custom allocator is implicated.

---

## Candidate 2: D3DPOOL_MANAGED textures — first-use GPU upload stall

**What it is.** All normal textures are created with `D3DPOOL_MANAGED`
(Direct3d9_TextureData.cpp:395, 432). In D3D9, MANAGED pool means the runtime keeps
a system-memory shadow copy and uploads to GPU VRAM on first-use — specifically on
the first `Present()` or `DrawPrimitive()` call that touches the texture. The upload
is synchronous-to-the-GPU from the CPU's perspective: the runtime detects the dirty
system-memory buffer, calls the GPU to DMA it, and the CPU stalls waiting for the
transfer to complete (or at least for the command to be submitted and acked).

**Zone-in context.** When zoning into the cantina, many textures are first-used.
In the D3D9 driver (WDDM model on Win10/11), the MANAGED pool upload goes through
the UMD → KMD → DMA path. Under WDDM, the very first Present() after N new MANAGED
textures have been DMAed can cause a brief GPU sync stall.

**Retail comparison.** The retail binary also uses D3DPOOL_MANAGED (it was the
standard D3D9 pattern in 2003). So this is NOT a new difference introduced by our
rebuild. However: the retail binary is 32-bit and has a fixed ~2GB address space;
our rebuilt client has LARGEADDRESSAWARE and can buffer more textures between
checkpoints. More importantly, on modern WDDM drivers there is an additional cost
that did not exist under XPDM (Win XP): WDDM's staging-buffer indirection and
residency tracking add overhead to MANAGED pool that was absent in the WinXP drivers
that the retail binary was tuned for.

**Magnitude: MED.** Not a new rebuilder regression per se, but the WDDM amplification
is real and untested. Per-frame hitches during zone-in that correlate with DrawPrimitive
calls touching new textures are the signature.

**What to measure:**
- GPU performance counters in PIX/RenderDoc: look for GPU-idle stalls at Present() during zone-in.
- Switch to `D3DPOOL_DEFAULT` + explicit `D3DPOOL_SYSTEMMEM` staging upload via `UpdateTexture()` for non-render-target textures. This gives the app explicit control over when the upload happens (pre-upload all zone-in textures before the first frame) rather than paying it per-draw.
- Count new MANAGED textures per frame during zone-in with a PixCounter.

---

## Candidate 3: OutputDebugString during shader rewrite — kernel round-trip per compile

**What it is.** In Debug builds, every shader rewrite emits via `DEBUG_REPORT_LOG_PRINT(true, ...)`:
- `Direct3d9_HlslRewrite.cpp:844` — emits for every #include rewrite during compilation.
- `Direct3d9_HlslRewrite.cpp:888` — emits for every main-source rewrite.
- `Direct3d9_VertexShaderData.cpp:700` — emits shader compile errors/warnings.

`REPORT_LOG_PRINT(true, ...)` calls `Report::setFlags(RF_log|RF_print)` then
`Report::puts()`, which calls `OutputDebugString(buffer)` (Report.cpp:145). Under a
debugger, `OutputDebugString` is a round-trip through a named kernel mutex and shared
memory (`DBWIN_BUFFER` protocol) — this can cost 1–5ms per call when a debugger
(Visual Studio, WinDbg) is attached. With 44 VS compiles each triggering multiple
rewrite log lines, the cumulative Debug overhead is significant.

**In Release builds:** `DEBUG_REPORT_LOG_PRINT` is defined to `NOP` (Report.h:65).
So this is Debug-only overhead.

**Magnitude (Debug): HIGH.** With a VS debugger attached and 44 VS compiles each
producing 2–5 OutputDebugString calls, this can add 100–500ms to the zone-in window
in Debug. This explains why the user observes "worse in Debug" (Evidence file).
In Release this is zero.

**Magnitude (Release): NONE.** Compile-error messages that use
`DEBUG_REPORT_LOG_PRINT` become no-ops. The `REPORT_LOG_PRINT(true, ...)` variant
(non-debug) is used for the MemoryManager shutdown summary only, not in the
compile path.

**What to measure:**
- Detach the debugger and test Debug build — if Debug hitches reduce significantly
  with no debugger attached, OutputDebugString is the cause.
- Check ETW/Procmon for DebugObject named events during zone-in.

---

## Candidate 4: _ITERATOR_DEBUG_LEVEL=2 in Debug — per-operation STL iterator validation

**What it is.** The SwgClient Debug vcxproj sets `_ITERATOR_DEBUG_LEVEL=2`
(SwgClient.vcxproj:200). IDL=2 enables full iterator validation in the MSVC STL:
every `std::vector::operator[]`, `std::map::find`, `begin()`/`end()` access is
validated at runtime with range checks and ownership checks. Modern MSVC STL with
IDL=2 is dramatically slower for container-heavy workloads than the original
STLport (which had debug mode off by default, or was shipped in Release mode with
no iterator validation).

**Zone-in relevance.** The zone-in path is extremely container-heavy:
- `Direct3d9_VertexShaderData.cpp` line 64: `std::vector<D3D_SHADER_MACRO>` rebuilt per compile.
- The global bytecode cache at line 143: `std::map<std::string, VsByteCode>` indexed per compile miss.
- The terrain shader cache, object lists, etc. all use `stdvector`/`stdmap` which resolve to `std::vector`/`std::map`.

STLport (used in the original code) did not have a concept of IDL=2 — it shipped
with a flat container implementation. Under IDL=2, even a simple `push_back` on a
`vector<D3D_SHADER_MACRO>` (44 entries × 44 compiles) does checked reallocs.
This is pure Debug tax, but it's non-trivial: IDL=2 can slow STL-heavy code by 5–20x
in Debug compared to Release.

**Release:** IDL=0 is set in all Release configs (vcxproj:261). Zero overhead.
**Debug:** IDL=2. Meaningful amplifier for container-heavy paths.

**Magnitude (Debug): HIGH-amplifier.** Not a standalone hitch cause but IDL=2
multiplies the cost of every STL operation in the already slow Debug path.

**What to measure:**
- Add `_ITERATOR_DEBUG_LEVEL=1` to Debug preprocessor defines (keeps some safety,
  removes the expensive ownership tracking) — measure zone-in hitch duration.
- IDL=0 in Debug (same as Release) will show the maximum speedup; IDL=1 is a
  reasonable middle ground.
- ETW CPU sampling in Debug should show % time in STL iterator-check inlined code.

---

## Candidate 5: ZlibFile decompression — lazy, first-read, on-main-thread

**What it is.** Assets in the TRE archives are zlib-compressed. When a ZlibFile is
first accessed (via `read()` or `seek()`), `createDecompressedMemoryFile()` is called
lazily (ZlibFile.cpp:121–123, 111–113). This decompresses the entire file on first read.
The decompression runs synchronously on the thread that first touches the file.
During zone-in, large numbers of TRE assets (textures, mesh geometry, shader
templates) are first-accessed on the main thread.

**Retail comparison.** This is the SAME code — not a rebuild regression. However:
MSVC v145's `zlib` build (linked at compile time via the engine's own zlib copy)
may be codegen'd differently. More meaningfully: MSVC v145 inlining behavior and
code-gen for tight decompression loops differs from VS2003. The retail binary was
likely compiled with aggressive PGO by SOE; our rebuild uses plain `/O2` without PGO.
Additionally, MSVC v145 at `/O2` without PGO may not inline the inflate inner loop
as aggressively as VS2003 + PGO on a zlib-heavy workload.

**Magnitude: LOW.** zlib inflate is bandwidth-bound, not heavily dependent on
compiler optimization. The lazy first-read pattern is the bigger latency issue, and
it's the same in both binaries. Not a meaningful rebuild regression.

---

## Candidate 6: C++20 EH / SEH overhead in compileVertexShaderFpGuarded

**What it is.** The VS compile path in `Direct3d9_VertexShaderData.cpp` wraps
`D3DCompile` in an SEH-guarded call `compileVertexShaderFpGuarded`. Under MSVC
v145 with C++20, mixing SEH (`__try`/`__except`) with C++ EH (`/EHsc`) in the same
translation unit forces the compiler to emit a frame-based unwind table for every
function in the TU that might have objects requiring destruction, even if it never
throws. This increases instruction-fetch overhead and stack frame setup.

**Magnitude: LOW.** SEH frame setup is a one-time cost per call frame entry, not
per-iteration work. With 44 compiles during zone-in, the overhead is at most a
few microseconds total. Not a meaningful contributor to visible hitches.

---

## Candidate 7: Demand-paging of large Debug image on first zone-in

**What it is.** The Debug SwgClient binary is significantly larger than the Release
binary (more symbols, debug info sections, RTC fill code). On Windows, demand-paging
means that code sections first executed during zone-in (which executes a much wider
code surface than the title screen) trigger page faults. Each hard-page-fault (kernel
round-trip from disk or page-file) costs ~1–10ms.

**Magnitude: MED in Debug / LOW in Release.** The first zone-in after a cold boot
is worst. In subsequent zone-ins on the same process the pages are warm in the
working set. This is a standard Debug-binary warmup cost, not specific to our rebuild,
but our binary is larger (more C++20 headers, heavier STL, more inlined template
instantiations). Superseded after first zone-in.

**What to measure:**
- Windows Performance Toolkit (WPT) `xperf` or Task Manager Page Faults column:
  count hard faults during zone-in vs subsequent zone-ins.
- Compare Debug vs Release page-fault count during zone-in.

---

## Candidate 8: `D3DCREATE_FPU_PRESERVE` — per-draw SSE/x87 mode sync cost

**What it is.** `D3DCREATE_FPU_PRESERVE` was just added (Direct3d9.cpp:1494).
This flag prevents D3D9 from clamping the x87 FPU to single precision, but it also
disables a driver micro-optimization: some D3D9 driver paths assume the FPU is
in single-precision mode and can skip the mode save/restore around FP instructions.
With FPU_PRESERVE the driver must save and restore the FPU control word on every
state-setting or draw call that it internally uses FP for.

**Magnitude: LOW.** The per-draw overhead is sub-microsecond. With thousands of
draws per frame the cumulative cost is measurable (perhaps 1–5% frame time) but
not a spike/hitch source. Not a zone-in-specific amplifier.

---

## Candidate 9: Modern MSVC STL string/map — allocation profile vs STLport

**What it is.** The original code used STLport. STLport used `node_alloc`, a
per-size-class free-list that bypassed the global allocator for small containers.
Modern MSVC STL (2019+) uses `std::allocator` which routes to `::operator new`
and thus to our `MemoryManager::allocate()`. Every `std::string` short-string-
optimization threshold in MSVC is 15 bytes (vs STLport's 16); `std::map` nodes
route through the global allocator.

**The specific zone-in impact:** the bytecode cache key at VertexShaderData.cpp:151
builds a `std::string` (fileName + \\x1f + key suffix) per lookup. The map lookup
itself does string comparisons. With MSVC STL each map node is a separate allocation
through MemoryManager. With STLport's node allocator, map nodes were pooled within
STLport's own size-class free-list (bypassing MemoryManager entirely for the common
case).

**Magnitude: MED-LOW.** This is a background-drag contribution. Each map node
allocation at zone-in goes through the MemoryManager tree search (Candidate 1).
The two amplify each other. Not a standalone spike source.

---

## Summary ranking: what actually matters for zone-in HITCHES

| # | Candidate | Config | Contribution | Key reason |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| 3 | OutputDebugString per rewrite/compile | Debug only | HIGH | 1–5ms per ODS call under debugger × many calls = 100–500ms aggregate Debug tax |
| 4 | _ITERATOR_DEBUG_LEVEL=2 | Debug only | HIGH-amplifier | 5–20x STL slowdown; amplifies every container op during the compile/load path |
| 7 | Demand-paging large Debug image | Debug (first zone-in) | MED | Hard page faults; warms after first zone-in |
| 2 | D3DPOOL_MANAGED first-use GPU upload | All configs | MED | WDDM staging overhead not present under WinXP XPDM; per-frame texture-touch stall |
| 1 | MemoryManager global CS + BST per alloc | All configs | MED-LOW | Background drag; free-list tree grows with fragmentation; exacerbated by modern STL routing through it |
| 9 | MSVC STL map/string — no node allocator | All configs | MED-LOW | Map nodes now through MemoryManager BST search (was bypassed by STLport node allocator) |
| 5 | ZlibFile lazy decompression | All configs | LOW | Same as retail; not a rebuild regression |
| 6 | SEH/EH in compile guard | All configs | LOW | One-time per-call, negligible magnitude |
| 8 | D3DCREATE_FPU_PRESERVE overhead | All configs | LOW | Sub-microsecond per draw |

---

## Key finding: the Debug hitches are artificially inflated by TWO independent taxes

The observation "worse in Debug" points to candidates 3 and 4 stacking:
- Every D3DCompile call (44 zone-in) triggers 2–5 `OutputDebugString` calls
  (via `DEBUG_REPORT_LOG_PRINT(true, ...)` in Direct3d9_HlslRewrite.cpp), each
  costing 1–5ms under a debugger.
- IDL=2 multiplies every STL container operation in the shader-compile and
  asset-load paths by 5–20x.

Neither of these taxes exist in Release. The Release hitches are therefore more
"honest" (just the D3DCompile time + candidate 2 MANAGED pool stalls), while Debug
adds a large synthetic inflation from ODS and IDL=2.

---

## Actionable measurements

1. **Isolate ODS overhead (Debug):** Detach VS debugger and re-test Debug build.
   The ODS calls become no-ops when no debugger listens; if Debug hitches shrink
   significantly this is confirmed.

2. **IDL=1 in Debug:** Change vcxproj Debug `_ITERATOR_DEBUG_LEVEL` from 2 to 1.
   Rebuild Debug. Measure zone-in time. Expected: 30–60% improvement in Debug
   hitch duration.

3. **MemoryManager BST drag:** Enable `ms_debugProfileAllocate` flag in a Debug
   build (DebugFlags "SharedMemoryManager/profileAllocate") and look at the
   allocate profiler block time in the PIX profiler during zone-in.

4. **D3DPOOL_MANAGED stall in Release:** Add a PixCounter counting CreateTexture
   calls per frame. In RenderDoc: look for GPU timeline gaps at Present() during
   zone-in frames — these are the MANAGED-pool upload stalls.

5. **DISABLE_MEMORY_MANAGER test:** In a scratch build, set `DISABLE_MEMORY_MANAGER 1`
   at MemoryManager.cpp:38 to fall through to CRT malloc. If Release zone-in
   improves measurably, pursue a size-class slab allocator or mimalloc replacement.

